The Ukraine on the Path to Europe
"East is east and west is west, and they will never meet," once said Rudyard Kipling.
Although the Ukraine is undoubtedly in the east, it is in the east of Europe.
When the country regained its independence ten years ago, European integration became the dominant goal for many of us.
The path to it, however, was not always paved with successes, if it was paved at all.
But the result of the parliamentary elections on March 31 has shown that the Ukrainians are still determined to go down this path.
I am a social democrat and was never a member of the communist party, although I was quite successful as a lawyer during the time of the Soviet Union.
It goes without saying that our "Soviet" heritage is largely responsible for the difficulties Ukraine has had in reconnecting with Europe.
After the collapse of the USSR, the country had an inefficient and militarized industry as well as an unprofessional bureaucratic apparatus.
The huge agricultural production areas were practically paralyzed by outdated machinery parks and the inertia of state-run agriculture in the Soviet style.
The rural population sank deep into dirt and poverty.
Low wages make life here very difficult, pensions are a joke, and the shadow economy is huge.
But our Soviet heritage does not justify everything.
We completely botched the reforms on our own.
Because often we wanted to import tried-and-tested concepts from the West - private property, free market economy, strict respect for human rights, the creation of a civil society, representative democracy - in a diluted form and thought this would somehow help us preserve socialist elements.
Despite these nostalgic tendencies in politics, the Supreme Court (the Parliament of Ukraine) has over the years adopted laws on civil rights and criminal law, land, family and economic rights, which is something like a revolution.
The acceptance of Western values in a society that had been cut off from European history for centuries was often painful, but has now gained momentum, although we do not necessarily see ourselves as a typical Western nation.
We see ourselves as open, sentimental, friendly, and family-oriented, but also chaotic and indifferent, sometimes irresponsible and lazy.
Nevertheless, we are Europeans.
You can see that on the streets and squares of Kyiv.
Today, motorists let pedestrians cross the street, as in Geneva or Munich (while pedestrians in Moscow still have to cross the street in safety from reckless drivers).
In Kyiv, there is now a lively café scene and friendly public squares where people can pause and enjoy life.
Youth learn English, German, and French, they can handle computers and surf the Internet in Internet cafés.
But these are only the whimsical digressions of someone who loves Kyiv very much.
The sober gaze of the professional politician, which I am, sees deeper changes.
In the last ten years, a development from total rejection of reforms through a policy of half-hearted reforms motivated by corruption to a gradual introduction of Western practices has taken place.
The administrative reform reflects this very clearly.
At first, the reform of the state provoked a hostile mood among both civil servants and ordinary citizens.
A drastic and ill-considered reduction of officials in the civil service began.
It was a "F-recipe" reform: the state must shrink, it was assumed, and then the government would run smoothly.
No one thought about the fact that countries like France or Switzerland somehow manage to thrive with large state apparatuses.
Because the problem is not only a problem of size, but also of organization and efficiency.
The realization that the government does not necessarily become better simply by cutting the red tape led us to the second stage of our reform process.
Gradually, the state was reformed in a more thoughtful manner.
New departments and positions for state secretaries with clearly defined areas of responsibility were established.
Thus, the work of the government ministries became more stable.
At first, the powers entrusted to these new areas were too broad to enable them to perform their work more effectively.
Now, they function more or less normally.
Ukrainians may sometimes be annoyed by these impersonal modern mechanisms, but they are increasingly accepting them as necessary (even though reluctantly).
Reasonable politicians also accept them.
Only radicals and populists - of which there are still too many among us - can afford to adopt an indifferent attitude towards a more efficient state.
Taming our radicals and the radical impulse was not easy.
Why?
Ukraine has been a province of the USSR and the tsarist empire for too long, the most important, but still a province.
This has shaped our mentality. For radicalism is a byproduct of provincial inferiority complexes.
An overwhelming feeling of inferiority and our efforts to deny it have led to the most scandalous moments in Ukrainian politics.
The provincial cannot possibly admit his own inferiority and refuses to learn from others.
To the extent that we shed our provincial impulse of having to defend ourselves, we open ourselves to the best of what others can offer us.
A century ago, the Ottoman Empire was mocked as "the sick man of Europe."
Since 1991, Ukrainians had to recognize that their country had inherited this sad title in the eyes of many Europeans.
Over the course of a decade, we may have even contributed to becoming even more sick, but the recent elections, which brought the Communists to lose their dominant position in the Supreme Council and significantly reduced the power of the "powerful parties" around President Kuchma, have pushed our provincial radicals to the edge of politics.
The reform parties and the European parties have won.
As European outsiders or at least as a people at the edge of Europe, we want to build a society in which there are no outsiders or marginalised groups.
As the great and already American writer Vladimir Nabokov said in the 70s: "Of all the achievements of nature, the most astonishing is probably the survival of the weakest."
The long, hardship-filled path towards Europe has helped a weak new nation to become strong and to survive.
